Path and ClassPath variables

A path is the address that tells the system where a file or directory is located, either absolutely (from root) or relatively (from current directory).
There are two related but distinct concepts in Java: CLASSPATH and Class (as in the java.lang.Class object), plus sometimes people confuse classpath variables with environment variables used to locate classes. 
________________________________________
CLASSPATH in Java
What is it?
CLASSPATH is an environment variable (or command-line parameter) that tells the Java Virtual Machine (JVM) and Java compiler where to look for user-defined classes and packages.
•	By default, JVM looks in the current directory (.).
•	If your classes are in other directories or JAR files, you must include them in the classpath.
________________________________________
Syntax examples
a) Environment variable (system-wide)
•	On Windows:
set CLASSPATH=C:\myclasses;C:\lib\myjar.jar;.
•	On Linux/Mac:
export CLASSPATH=/home/user/classes:/home/user/lib/mylib.jar:.
b) Command-line option
javac -cp “.;C:\jdbc\mysql-connector-j-9.5.0\mysql-connnector-j-9.5.0.jar” Database.java
java -cp “.;C:\jdbc\mysql-connector-j-9.5.0\mysql-connnector-j-9.5.0.jar” Database
Tip: -cp is shorthand for -classpath.
________________________________________
Notes
•	Multiple paths are separated by : (Linux/Mac) or ; (Windows).
•	If you don’t set CLASSPATH, the JVM uses . (current directory) by default.
javac -cp ".;E:\jtest\CORBAProject\jacorb\jacorb-3.9\lib\*;E:\jtest\CORBAProject\corba_lib\*" Server.java
java -cp ".;E:\jtest\CORBAProject\jacorb\jacorb-3.9\lib\*;E:\jtest\CORBAProject\corba_lib\*" Server

Summary Table
Concept	Purpose
CLASSPATH	Tells JVM/compiler where to find compiled class files / JARs
Class object (java.lang.Class)	Represents a Java class at runtime; used for reflection, metadata, dynamic instantiation
