2.	Can we give a parameter along with "new String("Java")" like this while creating and object?
Ans: This is exactly how constructors work. Yes, we can pass parameters while creating an object — if the class has a constructor that accepts parameters.
The line:
new String("Java")
works because String has a constructor that takes a String argument.
________________________________________
Step 2: What’s really happening?
When you write:
new String("Java");
Java is doing two things:
1.	Creating a new String object
2.	Calling this constructor internally:
String(String value)
So parameters go to the constructor, not to new itself.
________________________________________
Your own class example
Let’s mirror this idea with a custom class:
class Student {
    int id;

    Student(int id) {   // constructor with parameter
        this.id = id;
    }
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student(10); // passing parameter
    }
}
✔ This works because Student(int id) exists.
❌ If the constructor didn’t exist, Java would give a compile-time error.
________________________________________
Important rule to remember
Rule:
Parameters can be passed during object creation only through constructors.
