Quick tip
•	If you don’t write any constructor, Java gives a default no-argument constructor.
•	But if you write a parameterized constructor, the default no-arg constructor disappears unless you add it yourself.
________________________________________
 The rule
 Every class in Java has a constructor, even if you don’t write one.
•	If you don’t write any constructor, Java provides a default no-argument constructor automatically.
•	If you write a constructor yourself, Java does not provide a default one.
________________________________________
Example
Case 1: No constructor written
class Student {
    int id;
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student(); // works! default constructor used
    }
}
Case 2: Parameterized constructor written
class Student {
    int id;
    Student(int id) { // parameterized constructor
        this.id = id;
    }
}

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student(); // ❌ Error! No default constructor
        Student s2 = new Student(10); // ✅ Works
    }
}
________________________________________
Key points
•	Default constructor → automatically added if no constructor exists.
•	Parameterized constructor → you must call it with matching parameters.
Memory tip: “Java always gives a default constructor… until you write your own.”
