Package hierarchy in Java
========================================
Step 1: Package hierarchy in Java
•	In Java, packages are namespaces.
•	java is a top-level package name. It doesn’t contain classes directly. Instead, it has subpackages like:
o	java.lang
o	java.util
o	java.net
o	java.sql
✅ So technically, java itself is not a class container, only a namespace for subpackages.
________________________________________
Step 2: What “core package” means
•	The core Java library generally refers to classes in packages like:
o	java.lang (mandatory, contains Object, String, etc.)
o	java.util (collections, date, etc.)
o	java.io, java.net, java.sql (standard APIs)
•	java.lang is considered the root core package, because it’s automatically imported and contains the root class Object.
________________________________________
Step 3: Where “everything grows from”
•	Inheritance-wise: Everything in Java grows from java.lang.Object, not from the package java.
•	java.lang is the real root package for core classes.
•	java is just the top-level namespace; think of it like a folder that organizes subfolders (java.lang, java.util, etc.).
________________________________________
Analogy (folder structure)
java/               <- top folder (namespace)
  lang/             <- root core package
    Object.class
    String.class
  util/             <- subpackage
    Scanner.class
    ArrayList.class
  net/              <- subpackage
    URL.class
•	Everything inherits from Object (in java.lang)
•	The “java” folder/package is just a container for these subpackages
________________________________________
Key takeaway:
Inheritance and “core” start from java.lang, not java.
java is just the top-level namespace for organizing the subpackages.

Show the hierarchy of "System" class?
Perfect! Let’s carefully go step by step so you can visualize the hierarchy of the System class.
________________________________________
Step 1: Which package it’s in
•	System belongs to the java.lang package:
java.lang.System
•	Because it’s in java.lang, it is automatically imported in every Java program.
________________________________________
Step 2: Inheritance
•	System is a final class:
public final class System
•	Final classes cannot be subclassed.
•	It directly extends java.lang.Object, and does not have any intermediate superclass.
________________________________________
Step 3: Class hierarchy
So the hierarchy looks like this:
java.lang.Object
        ↑
java.lang.System
•	That’s it — simple and direct
•	Even though it has many static methods and fields (like System.out, System.in, System.err), it does not extend any other class.
________________________________________
Step 4: Notes to remember
1.	System is final, so no subclass can extend it.
2.	It inherits methods from Object, like toString(), hashCode(), equals().
3.	All its fields/metvhods are static utility features (like I/O, environment properties, time).

Show the hierarchy of "println()" method?
println() is often confused as belonging to System, but it’s actually inside another class. Let’s carefully build the hierarchy.
________________________________________
Step 1: Where println() lives
•	You usually call it like this:
System.out.println("Hello");
•	System.out is a static field of System:
public static final PrintStream out;
•	So println() is not a method of System, but a method of java.io.PrintStream.
________________________________________
Step 2: PrintStream class hierarchy
•	PrintStream is a class in java.io
•	It extends java.io.FilterOutputStream, which extends java.io.OutputStream, which extends java.lang.Object
So the class hierarchy looks like this:
java.lang.Object
        ↑
java.io.OutputStream
        ↑
java.io.FilterOutputStream
        ↑
java.io.PrintStream
•	println() is defined in PrintStream, so it inherits nothing; it’s a concrete method in PrintStream.
________________________________________
Step 3: Summary of method call
•	System.out → reference to PrintStream
•	System.out.println() → calls the method inside PrintStream
•	Methods like println() ultimately come from PrintStream, which inherits from Object through OutputStream chain
________________________________________
Step 4: Quick mental diagram
Object
  │
OutputStream
  │
FilterOutputStream
  │
PrintStream
  │
println(), print(), printf() ...
•	Important: System just provides the out reference; it does not define println() itself.

Inner class example in Java?
What is an Inner Class?
An inner class is a class defined inside another class.
Why use it?
•	It logically belongs to the outer class
•	It can access private data of the outer class
•	Helps organize code
________________________________________
Simple Inner Class Example
Look at this outer class with an inner class inside it:
class Outer {
    int x = 10;

    class Inner {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("x = " + x);
        }
    }
}
What’s happening?
•	Outer is the main class
•	Inner is inside Outer
•	Inner can directly access x (even though it’s not public)
________________________________________
Creating an Inner Class Object
This part is important
class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Outer obj = new Outer();          // outer object
        Outer.Inner in = obj.new Inner(); // inner object
        in.show();
    }
}
Key idea 
You cannot create an inner class object without an outer class object.
________________________________________
Output
x = 10
________________________________________

What is wrong with this statement?
static int x=5;
The statement itself:
static int x = 5;
By itself, this line is NOT wrong in Java.
So the real question is: where is this written?

Step 1: Possible places this line could appear
Think about these options: :
1.	Inside a normal class
2.	Inside a static nested class
3.	Inside a method
4.	Inside a non-static inner class
Some of these are allowed… some are not.
Step 2: Key rule to remember 🧠
Java has a strict rule:
❌ A non-static inner class cannot have static variables
✅ Except static final constants

Step 3: So when is this statement WRONG?
This line is wrong ❌ if it is written inside a non-static inner class, like this:
class Outer {
    class Inner {
        static int x = 5;  // ❌ ERROR
    }
}
Java will complain because:
•	Inner classes are tied to an object
•	static members belong to the class, not an object

Step 4: When is it perfectly OK?
✅ Valid cases:
class Test {
    static int x = 5;   // OK
}
class Outer {
    static class Inner {
        static int x = 5;   // OK
    }
}


How can we define "static class" for class as the class has only two modifiers default "package-private" and "public"?
Key idea (the core answer)
You are 100% correct that a top-level class can have only two access modifiers:
•	public
•	default (package-private)
So…
There is NO such thing as a “static top-level class” in Java.

Then what is a “static class”?
When people say static class, they actually mean:
static nested class, not a top-level class.
Example:
class Outer {
    static class Inner {
        // this is called a "static class"
    }
}
Here:
•	Outer → top-level class
•	Inner → nested class
•	static applies to the nested class, not the top-level class
________________________________________
Why is this allowed?
Because nested classes are members of another class, just like:
•	fields
•	methods
And members CAN be static.
So:
•	❌ Top-level class → cannot be static
•	✅ Nested class → can be static

Compare: inner vs static nested class 🧠
Feature	             Inner class	           Static nested class
Needs outer object	           ✅ Yes	          ❌ No
Can have static members	           ❌ No	          ✅ Yes
Access outer instance vars	           ✅ Yes	          ❌ No

Common exam sentence (important!)
“Java does not support static top-level classes.
However, Java supports static nested classes.”
________________________________________
Complete Running Example: Static Nested Class
Code (single file)
class Outer {

    static int x = 10;   // static member of outer class

    // static nested class
    static class StaticInner {
        void display() {
            System.out.println("x = " + x);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // creating object of static nested class
        Outer.StaticInner obj = new Outer.StaticInner();
        obj.display();
    }
}

Output
x = 10

Step-by-step understanding 🧠
Why is this called a “static class”?
•	StaticInner is inside Outer
•	It is marked static
•	So its correct name is static nested class

Important observations
•	✅ No Outer object is created
•	✅ We directly use Outer.StaticInner
•	✅ Static nested class can access only static members of Outer
❌ If x were non-static, this would fail.

Key difference from inner class
If this were a non-static inner class, we would need:
Outer o = new Outer();
Outer.Inner i = o.new Inner();
But here:
Outer.StaticInner obj = new Outer.StaticInner();
Much simpler ✔

One-line exam definition 
A static nested class is a nested class declared with the static keyword and does not require an instance of the outer class.

