1.	 What is an interface in Java?
An interface is like a blueprint for classes. It defines methods that a class must implement, but it does not provide the method body (except for default/static methods in modern Java).
Think of it like a contract:
“If you implement me, you must provide these methods.”
________________________________________
2.	Key points about interfaces
1.	All methods in an interface are abstract by default (no body).
2.	Variables are public, static, and final by default.
3.	A class can implement multiple interfaces (unlike classes — no multiple inheritance).
