4.3.	Handling Exceptions: Try, Catch, Finally, Throws, and Throw keywords, Creating Exception Class

Exceptions are errors that show up when something impossible is tried. Like any value divide by 0, infinitive plus infinitive, infinitive minus infinitive, infinitive divide by 0, 0 divide by 0 etc. 
There are five keywords in Java that we use for handling exceptions. They are:
Try, catch, finally, throws, throw

Types of exception
In Java, exceptions are either:
1.	Checked Exception → must be declared with throws
2.	Unchecked Exception → extends RuntimeException, no throws needed
1.	What is a Checked Exception?
A checked exception is an exception that the Java compiler forces you to handle.
•	You must either:
1.	Handle it with a try-catch block, or
2.	Declare it in the method signature using throws
•	If you don’t, the code won’t compile.
________________________________________
Examples of checked exceptions
•	IOException (file or input/output errors)
•	SQLException (database errors)
•	FileNotFoundException (file not found)
import java.io.*;

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            FileReader file = new FileReader("abc.txt"); // may throw FileNotFoundException
        } catch (FileNotFoundException e) {
            System.out.println("File not found!");
        }
    }
}
Here, the compiler forces you to handle FileNotFoundException.
________________________________________
Key point
•	Checked exceptions extend Exception (but not RuntimeException)
•	They are “checked” at compile time — that’s why the compiler complains if you don’t handle them.
2.	What is an Unchecked Exception?
An unchecked exception is an exception that the compiler does NOT force you to handle.
•	It occurs at runtime.
•	Usually caused by programming errors, like dividing by zero or using a null reference.
•	It extends RuntimeException.
________________________________________
 Examples
1.	ArithmeticException – dividing by zero
int x = 10 / 0; // Throws ArithmeticException at runtime
2.	NullPointerException – calling a method on null
String s = null;
System.out.println(s.length()); // Throws NullPointerException
3.	ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException – invalid array access
int[] arr = {1,2,3};
System.out.println(arr[5]); // Throws ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
________________________________________
Key point
•	You don’t need try-catch for unchecked exceptions, though you can use it if you want.
•	They are runtime exceptions, unlike checked exceptions which the compiler forces you to handle.
Example:
“Try” block defines the exception block, if there is an exception in that block then “catch” block handles that exception and don’t let your software system crash. “Finally” block runs always. “Throws” block is used with method and “throw” is used inside the method and handles the exception.
Example (try, catch, finally)
import java.lang.*;
public class Main
{
public static void main(String[] arg)
{
try
{
int a = 10;
int b = 0;
system.out.println(a/b);
}
catch(Exception e)   //grammar of catch
{
system.out.println(“Error!”);
}
finally
{
system.out.println(“Completed!!!”);
}
}
}

Example (throws, throw)

import java.lang.*;

class Age
{
static void checkAge(int age) throws Exception
{
if(age<18)
{
throw new Exception ("Invalid Age!");
}
System.out.println("Valid Age!");
}
}

public class Main
{
public static void main(String[] arg)
{
Age a = new Age();
try
{
a.checkAge(15);
}
catch(Exception e)
{
System.out.println(e.getMessage());
}
finally
{
System.out.println("Completed!");
}
}
}


