1.4. Concurrency: Introduction, Thread States, Writing Multithreaded Programs, Thread Properties, Thread Synchronization, Thread Priorities 
Concurrency in Java (definition)
Concurrency in Java is the ability of a Java program to execute multiple threads (paths of execution) so that more than one task can progress at the same time.
Important:
•	They overlap in time
•	They don’t have to run at the exact same instant
Example analogy
•	Program = a whole office building
•	Thread (path of execution) = a single worker inside the office doing a task
•	Multiple workers (threads) can work at the same time in the same building (program).
________________________________________
Key points
1.	Every Java program has at least one thread — the main thread.
2.	Threads allow parallel execution — e.g., GUI responsive while downloading a file.
3.	In Java, you can create threads by:
a.	Extending Thread class
b.	Implementing Runnable interface 
a.	Example (Extending Thread class)
// Step 1: Create a class that extends Thread
class MyThread extends Thread {

    // Step 2: Override the run() method
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running");
    }
}

// Step 3: Use the thread
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyThread t1 = new MyThread(); // create thread object
        t1.start();                  // start the thread
    }
}

b.	Example (Implementing Runnable interface)
// Step 1: Implement Runnable
class MyTask implements Runnable {

    // Step 2: Implement run()
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread is running using Runnable");
    }
}

// Step 3: Use Thread to start it
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        MyTask task = new MyTask();     // task object
        	//task.start();  // this will not work, explanation is given below
Thread t1 = new Thread(task);   // thread object
        t1.start();                     // start thread
    }
}


Explanation of above thread example with Runnable
========================================================
Step 1: Look at what you did

MyTask task = new MyTask();   // ✅ task is Runnable
task.start();                 // ❌ Error
Problem: task is a Runnable object.

Runnable interface does NOT have a start() method.
Only Thread objects have the start() method.

Step 2: Correct way using Runnable
You must wrap your Runnable in a Thread:
MyTask task = new MyTask();   // Runnable object
Thread t1 = new Thread(task); // Thread object
t1.start();                   // ✅ Correct: starts the thread
•	Now start() is called on the Thread, which will internally call task.run().
________________________________________
Step 3: Why this design exists
•	Java separates task definition (Runnable) from thread execution machinery (Thread class).
•	This allows your task to extend another class (since Java doesn’t allow multiple inheritance) and still run as a thread.
________________________________________
✅ Key takeaway
You cannot call start() on a Runnable object. Only Thread objects have start().

