Question No. 3
Therefore its all happening in JVM?
Exactly! 
Let’s break it down carefully.
________________________________________
Step 1: Where threads live
All threads in Java — whether the main thread, a thread from extends Thread, or a thread from implements Runnable — are managed by the JVM.
•	JVM = Java Virtual Machine
•	JVM creates, schedules, and runs threads on the underlying OS
So all the stuff we wrote (main(), run(), etc.) is executed inside the JVM, which in turn maps it to real CPU threads.
________________________________________
Step 2: What JVM does for threads
When you call start():
1.	JVM creates a new thread at the OS level
2.	JVM calls the run() method in that thread
3.	JVM schedules threads concurrently
4.	JVM ends the thread when run() finishes
Even the main thread is created and managed by JVM automatically.
________________________________________
Step 3: Summary
•	All Java code → runs inside JVM
•	Threads (main, t1, etc.) → paths of execution inside JVM
•	JVM interacts with the OS to actually run the threads
Think of JVM as a thread manager and executor. 🧠

Question No. 4
run( ) seems to be normal methods that we create in any class. So. when we create a class object and access the method in that class through object then is it also a thread?
Ans: This is a super important distinction! Let’s think carefully.________________________________________
Step 1: Normal method vs thread method
When you write a normal class method:
class MyClass {
    void myMethod() {
        System.out.println("Hello");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyClass obj = new MyClass();
        obj.myMethod();  // calling like normal
    }
}
•	myMethod() runs on the main thread
•	No new thread is created
•	It’s just code executed sequentially
________________________________________
Step 2: run() in threads
Compare with a thread:
class MyTask implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread running");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyTask task = new MyTask();
        Thread t = new Thread(task);
        t.start();  // <--- new thread!
    }
}
•	run() is not a thread by itself
•	Only when start() is called on a Thread object, JVM creates a new thread, which executes run()
•	If you just call task.run() directly → it’s like a normal method, no new thread is created
________________________________________
Step 3: Key rule to remember 🧠
A method (even run()) is NOT a thread by itself.
Only a Thread object executing that method via start() becomes a thread.



