Simple examples of threads 
Think of a Java program that:
•	Downloads a file
•	Plays music
•	Responds to user input
•	All without freezing.
That’s concurrency.
Concurrency vs Parallelism (very important)
Concurrency	 Parallelism
Tasks overlap in time	                       Tasks run at same time
Possible on single CPU	                       Needs multiple cores
About structure	                       About hardware
Java supports both, but concurrency is the base idea.
________________________________________
How Java achieves concurrency
Java uses:
•	Threads
•	Thread scheduling
•	Synchronization tools
Main concept to remember:
One program → multiple threads
________________________________________
Why concurrency is needed
•	Better performance
•	Responsive applications
•	Efficient CPU usage
________________________________________
Quick check
Can concurrency exist on a single-core processor?
(Answer Yes or No — then we’ll continue 👍)
Ans: Yes

Parallelism vs Concurrency
•	Concurrency: tasks overlap in time (can switch back and forth)
•	Parallelism: tasks literally run at the same exact time
________________________________________
Single CPU situation
•	A single-core CPU can only execute one instruction at a time
•	It can switch between tasks quickly → gives the illusion of doing multiple tasks at once
•	✅ This is concurrency, not true parallelism
________________________________________
True parallelism
•	Needs multiple cores (multi-core CPU)
•	Each core can run a thread simultaneously
________________________________________
Quick answer to your question
No, true parallelism cannot occur on a single CPU.
But concurrency can.

“Overlap in time” ✅
•	Means tasks are active during the same overall period, but not necessarily at the exact same instant.
•	On a single CPU, the CPU switches between tasks rapidly, so it looks like they are happening together.
________________________________________
Example (single CPU)
Time: 0ms   1ms   2ms   3ms   4ms   5ms
Task A:  ████
Task B:      ████
•	Tasks take turns on the CPU
•	They overlap in the timeline, but only one is actually running at any instant
________________________________________
2️⃣ True Parallelism (multi-core CPU)
Core 1: ████  Task A
Core 2: ████  Task B
•	Both run exactly at the same time
•	This is parallelism, not just overlap
________________________________________
Quick way to remember
•	Concurrency = “tasks share the same time period” (can be interleaved)
•	Parallelism = “tasks literally run at the same moment”

What are Thread States?
Thread States are core to understanding concurrency. Thread states describe the current condition of a thread during its life cycle (born to death of thread inside the JVM).
In Java, a thread can be in one of 6 states.
________________________________________
The 6 Thread States (Java)
1. NEW
•	Thread object is created
•	start() has not been called yet
Thread t = new Thread(); // NEW
________________________________________
2. RUNNABLE
•	Thread is ready to run or running
•	CPU decides when it actually runs
t.start(); // RUNNABLE
________________________________________
3. BLOCKED
•	Thread is waiting to acquire(obtain) a lock
•	Another thread is using the resource
Note: sleep(), wait(), join() are always used with try, catch.
________________________________________
4. WAITING
•	Thread waits indefinitely
•	Until another thread signals it
Example methods:
•	wait()
•	join()

Note: sleep(), wait(), join() are always used with try, catch.
________________________________________
5. TIMED_WAITING
•	Thread waits for a fixed time
Example methods:
•	sleep(1000)
•	join(1000)
Note: sleep(), wait(), join() are always used with try, catch.
________________________________________
