Is object lock acquired automatically when "thread object" is created? 
Short answer (hold this thought)
 No. An object lock is not acquired automatically when a thread object is created.
Now let’s understand when a lock is acquired.
________________________________________
Step 1: What is an object lock?
In Java:
•	Every object has a lock (monitor)
•	But that lock is idle most of the time
Important idea:
A lock exists whether or not threads use it
________________________________________
Step 2: When is the lock actually acquired?
A lock is acquired only when a thread enters:
•	a synchronized method, or
•	a synchronized(obj) block
Example conceptually:
•	Creating a thread ❌ no lock
•	Calling start() ❌ no lock
•	Entering synchronized code ✅ lock acquired
________________________________________
Step 3: Key clarification (very important)
A Thread object and a lock object are different things.
•	Creating a Thread object → just creates an object
•	A thread acquires a lock on some object only when it tries to enter synchronized code on that object
The lock might be:
•	this
•	some shared object
•	a class object (for static synchronized)
________________________________________
One-line exam-ready answer
Object lock is acquired only when a thread enters a synchronized method or block, not when a thread object is created.
