Does "normal object" lock also need "synchronized code" to acquire lock?
Yes — exactly 
But let’s make sure you understand why, not just memorize it.
________________________________________
Step 1: One clear rule (very important)
Any object’s lock — normal object or Thread object — is acquired only by synchronized code.
There is no automatic lock acquisition.
________________________________________
Step 2: Think it through
Ask yourself:
If I just create an object like this:
MyClass obj = new MyClass();
Did any thread say “I want exclusive access to this object”?
❌ No — so no lock is taken.
________________________________________
Step 3: When does a normal object’s lock get acquired?
Only when a thread enters:
synchronized(obj) {
    // critical section
}
or
synchronized void method() {
    // lock on 'this'
}
At that moment:
•	the thread requests the object’s lock
•	if free → lock is acquired
•	if not → thread waits
________________________________________
Step 4: Key sentence to remember (exam gold ⭐)
In Java, object locks are passive; they are acquired only on demand by synchronized code.
