When is "object lock released" in Java?
Great — this is the other half of locking
Let’s reason it out carefully.
________________________________________
Step 1: Recall how a lock is acquired
You already know:
An object lock is acquired only when a thread enters synchronized code.
So now ask yourself the mirror question:
 When does a thread stop needing exclusive access?
________________________________________
Step 2: Core rule (very important)
An object lock is released automatically when a thread exits the synchronized block or synchronized method.
“Exit” can happen in three ways.
________________________________________
Step 3: The 3 situations when a lock is released
1.	Normal completion
synchronized(obj) {
    // code finishes normally
}
✔ Lock released when control leaves the block
________________________________________
2.	Exception occurs
synchronized(obj) {
    int x = 10 / 0;  // exception
}
✔ Lock released even if an exception occurs
(This is guaranteed by Java.)
________________________________________
3.	Return statement
synchronized(obj) {
    return;
}
✔ Lock released before returning
________________________________________
Step 4: Very important clarification 
Locks are NOT released when:
•	sleep() is called ❌
•	yield() is called ❌
•	thread is paused in execution ❌
Only exiting synchronized code releases the lock.
(We’ll talk about wait() separately — that’s a special case.)
________________________________________
One-line exam-ready answer
An object lock is released automatically when a thread exits the synchronized block or method, whether normally or due to an exception.
