Do sleep(), yield(), wait() methods cause "thread waiting" state?
________________________________________
Step 1: sleep()
•	Purpose: Pauses the thread for a specified time.
•	Thread state: Goes to TIMED_WAITING.
•	Important: The thread keeps any locks it holds.
•	Waiting type: Time-based waiting, not “waiting for a resource”.
✅ Example: Thread.sleep(1000); → thread pauses 1 second, then becomes runnable again.
________________________________________
Step 2: yield()
•	Purpose: Suggests to the scheduler to let other threads of same priority run.
•	Thread state: Still RUNNABLE — it doesn’t go to waiting!
•	Important: It’s just a hint. No lock release, no guaranteed pause.
✅ Think of it as saying: “Hey CPU, if someone else wants a turn, please run them first.”
________________________________________
Step 3: wait()
•	Purpose: Used inside a synchronized block to wait for a condition.
•	Thread state: Goes to WAITING (or TIMED_WAITING if timed).
•	Important: Releases the object lock while waiting!
•	Resumes only when notify() or notifyAll() is called.
✅ Example:
synchronized(obj) {
    obj.wait();  // releases lock, waits for notify
}
________________________________________
Step 4: Quick summary table (exam-friendly)
Method	Thread state	Releases lock?	Notes
sleep(ms)	TIMED_WAITING	No	Time-based pause
yield()	RUNNABLE	No	Hint to scheduler
wait()	WAITING / TIMED_WAITING	Yes	Waits for notify
________________________________________
