Explanation of errors in above program
=================================

What's wrong with below code?
import java.lang.*; 
class MyTest implements Runnable 
{ 
public void run() //thread starting point
 { System.out.println("Hello! Thread"); 
}
 }
public class Main 
{ 
public static void main(String[] arg) 
{ 
MyTest obj = new MyTest(); //thread object created 
Thread t1 = new Thread(obj); 
t1.start(); //new thread created 
synchronized(t1) 
{ 
t1.sleep(2000); 
} 
System.out.println("Successfully executed all operations !!!"); 
}
} 
Ah! - there’s a classic threading mistake here. Let’s analyze carefully, step by step.
________________________________________
Step 1: The synchronized(t1) block
synchronized(t1) {
    t1.sleep(2000);
}
•	You’re synchronizing on t1, which is okay, but not necessary here.
•	Problem: sleep() is a static method, inherited from Thread, and it always affects the current thread, not the thread object you call it on.
So:
t1.sleep(2000);
❌ This does not pause t1. It pauses the main thread for 2 seconds.
________________________________________
Step 2: Correct usage of sleep()
•	You should call:
Thread.sleep(2000);  // pauses the current thread
•	Or, if you want t1 to sleep, you must put sleep() inside the run() method of that thread.
________________________________________
Step 3: Optional issue: unnecessary synchronized
•	Synchronizing on t1 here is pointless because sleep() does not require a lock.
•	sleep() does not release or acquire locks — it just pauses the current thread.
________________________________________
Step 4: Corrected version
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] arg) throws InterruptedException {
        MyTest obj = new MyTest();
        Thread t1 = new Thread(obj);
        t1.start();  // new thread runs

        Thread.sleep(2000);  // pause main thread, not t1

        System.out.println("Successfully executed all operations !!!");
    }
}
✅ Notes:
•	Added throws InterruptedException because sleep() throws it.
•	Removed unnecessary synchronized.
________________________________________
Step 5: Key conceptual takeaway
•	Thread.sleep() pauses the CURRENT thread, not the thread object you call it on.
•	Only wait() requires an object lock and releases it.
________________________________________
