Show above example with "synchronized(t1)"?
Absolutely — we can keep synchronized(t1), but we need to understand its role carefully.
________________________________________
Key point before coding
•	synchronized(t1) acquires the lock on t1
•	sleep() does not release the lock, so the main thread holds t1’s lock while sleeping
•	t1 thread runs independently, nothing stops it
This is mostly a demonstration — in real programs, this synchronized here is unnecessary.
________________________________________
Example with synchronized(t1)
class MyTest implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + ": Hello! Thread started");
        try {
            Thread.sleep(1000);  // thread pauses itself
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + " interrupted");
        }
        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + ": Hello! Thread finished");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] arg) throws InterruptedException {
        MyTest obj = new MyTest();
        Thread t1 = new Thread(obj, "T1");
        t1.start();  // new thread created

        synchronized(t1) {
            System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + ": Main thread sleeping while holding t1 lock");
            Thread.sleep(2000);  // main thread sleeps
        }

        System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName() + ": Successfully executed all operations !!!");
    }
}
________________________________________
Step 1: What happens
1.	t1.start() → starts a new thread “T1”
2.	Main thread enters synchronized(t1) → acquires t1’s lock
3.	Main thread calls Thread.sleep(2000) → main thread pauses, t1 still runs independently
4.	Main thread wakes up → releases t1 lock → prints final message
________________________________________
Step 2: Important notes
•	Main thread holds t1 lock while sleeping, but t1 thread does not need that lock, so it runs freely.
•	Using synchronized(t1) here does not control the other thread.
•	sleep() never releases the lock.


