What is Thread Synchronization?
•	Thread synchronization = coordination between threads to avoid conflicts
•	When multiple threads access shared resources (like variables, files, or objects), race conditions can occur.
•	Synchronization ensures that only one thread at a time can access the shared resource.
________________________________________
Why synchronization is needed
Example problem (without synchronization):
class Counter {
    int count = 0;

    void increment() {
        count++;  // not atomic, can cause wrong results if multiple threads run concurrently
    }
}
•	If Thread 1 reads count=0 and Thread 2 also reads count=0, they both increment → count becomes 1 instead of 2. They could interleave (to arrange by alternating layers) and happen at a same time, multiple threads may block each other, leading to wrong result. So, to avoid this, we have to use keyword “synchronized” as in below example.
________________________________________

How to synchronize in Java
Method 1: synchronized method
class Counter {
    int count = 0;

    // only one thread can execute this at a time
    synchronized void increment() {
        count++;
    }
}
•	Any thread calling increment() will lock the object until done. Only one thread at a time could execute, multiple threads don’t block each other.
________________________________________
Method 2: synchronized block
class Counter {
    int count = 0;

    void increment() {
        synchronized(this) {  // lock only this block


            count++;
        }
    }
}
•	More fine-grained control, only locks critical section instead of the whole method. Example 1 and example 2 both works as same.
________________________________________
Key points
Concept	                   Notes
Lock (Monitor)	                   Each object has a lock; synchronized acquires it
Critical section	                   Part of code that must not be accessed by multiple threads simultaneously
Thread-safe	                   Class is safe for concurrent use
Deadlock	                   When two threads wait forever for each other’s locks
________________________________________
Quick check
If two threads call a synchronized method on the same object, can they execute it at the same time?
(Answer Yes or No)
No
Exactly ✅ — they cannot execute a synchronized method at the same time on the same object.
•	When one thread enters a synchronized method, it locks the object.
•	Any other thread trying to call a synchronized method on that same object will wait until the lock is released.
