4.4.	Byte Stream Classes, Character Stream Classes, Random Access File, Reading and Writing Objects.

What is a stream in Java?
In Java, a stream is a sequence of data elements that flows from a source to a destination. It is an abstraction for input and output — reading from or writing to a file, memory, network, etc.
Think of it as a pipe: data goes in or out one piece at a time, without worrying about the underlying storage.
________________________________________
1. Types of streams in Java
a) Based on data type
1.	Byte Streams (InputStream / OutputStream)
o	Handle raw binary data (bytes).
o	Classes: FileInputStream, FileOutputStream, BufferedInputStream, BufferedOutputStream
2.	FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("data.bin");
3.	int b = fis.read(); // reads one byte
4.	fis.close();
5.	Character Streams (Reader / Writer)
o	Handle text data (characters).
o	Classes: FileReader, FileWriter, BufferedReader, PrintWriter
6.	FileReader fr = new FileReader("data.txt");
7.	int c = fr.read(); // reads one character
8.	fr.close();
________________________________________
b) Based on direction
1.	Input Stream – reads data from a source
2.	Output Stream – writes data to a destination
________________________________________
c) Based on functionality
•	Filter Streams: Enhance other streams (e.g., BufferedReader, BufferedOutputStream)
•	Data Streams: Read/write primitive types easily (DataInputStream, DataOutputStream)
•	Object Streams: Read/write objects (ObjectInputStream, ObjectOutputStream)
________________________________________
2. Key points
•	Streams do not store data; they just transport it.
•	Streams can be chained: e.g., wrap FileInputStream in BufferedInputStream for efficiency.
•	Java treats all I/O as streams, whether it’s a file, console, or network.
________________________________________
3. Analogy
•	Water pipe analogy:
o	Source → Pipe → Destination
o	Byte/Character = water molecules
o	Buffered stream = pipe with a tank to make flow efficient
________________________________________
Summary
A stream in Java is a sequence of data that flows from a source (input) to a destination (output). Streams abstract the details of where data comes from or goes to, allowing uniform handling of I/O.

