What’s happening (conceptual)
•	FileInputStream → opens the image file
•	read() → reads one byte at a time
•	-1 → means end of file
•	We don’t interpret the data as characters (very important!)
Step 1: What does read() return?
In this line from Example 1:
byteData = fis.read();
 read() returns an int, not a byte.
________________________________________
Step 2: Why not return byte?
Because read() needs to return two kinds of values:
1.	Actual byte data → values from 0 to 255
2.	End of file signal → -1
A byte in Java can only store:
-128 to 127
So -1 would clash with real data ❌
________________________________________
Step 3: Why int byteData is needed
An int can safely hold:
•	0–255 → valid byte data
•	-1 → end of file
That’s why we write:
int byteData;
and check:
while ((byteData = fis.read()) != -1)
________________________________________
Step 4: Simple memory trick 🧠
Byte stream reads bytes, but returns int to signal EOF

Example (Byte Stream – reading an image and displaying)
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.awt.*;
import java.awt.image.*;
import javax.imageio.ImageIO;
import javax.swing.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Step 1: Open FileInputStream
            FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("photo.jpg");

            // Step 2: Read bytes into a BufferedImage
            BufferedImage image = ImageIO.read(fis); // converts bytes to image
            fis.close(); // close the stream

            // Step 3: Display the image in a JFrame
            JFrame frame = new JFrame("Display Image");
            frame.setDefaultCloseOperation(JFrame.EXIT_ON_CLOSE);

            JLabel label = new JLabel(new ImageIcon(image));
            frame.getContentPane().add(label, BorderLayout.CENTER);

            frame.pack(); // fit window to image
            frame.setVisible(true);

        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}

