Character Stream Classes
=====================
Character stream classes are used in text data files. The content in a text data file are readable by humans. 
Important Points
Operation	       Classes / Methods Used	Notes
Create file	   File.createNewFile()	Returns true if file is created
Write file	   FileWriter, BufferedWriter	Use close() to save changes
Read file	FileReader, BufferedReader, Scanner	Read line by line or character by character
Delete file	   File.delete()	Returns true if deletion successful
Check existence	   File.exists()	Returns true if file exists

 Why Java created Character Stream Classes
Text isn’t just bytes — it has:
•	characters
•	encodings (Unicode, UTF-8, etc.)

So Java introduced character streams to handle text correctly.
The foundation of character streams
Just like byte streams had two parents, character streams also have two abstract parent classes:
•	Reader → reads characters
•	Writer → writes characters
Think of it as:
InputStream  → bytes
Reader       → characters
Important character stream subclasses
Here are the main ones you should remember:
Readers
•	FileReader → reads characters from a file
•	BufferedReader → reads efficiently + readLine()
Writers
•	FileWriter → writes characters to a file
•	BufferedWriter → writes efficiently

Packages for File Handling
In Java, file operations are mostly in the java.io and java.nio.file packages:
•	java.io.File → to represent files and directories
•	java.io.FileReader / FileWriter → to read/write text files
•	java.io.BufferedReader / BufferedWriter → efficient reading/writing
•	java.nio.file.Files → newer API for reading/writing files
