Random Access File
===============

Sequential access files (text & binary)
✅ Write sequentially
✅ Read sequentially
❌ Random (direct) reading not possible
You must start at the beginning and move forward record by record.
➡️ So:
Write sequentially and read sequentially in sequential access files ✔️
________________________________________
Random access files
✅ Write sequentially (if you don’t move the file pointer)
✅ Read sequentially
✅ Read randomly using seek()
✅ Write randomly using seek()
Example:
RandomAccessFile raf = new RandomAccessFile("data.dat", "rw");

// sequential write
raf.writeInt(10);
raf.writeInt(20);

// random read
raf.seek(0);
int x = raf.readInt();
➡️ So:
Write sequentially and read randomly in random access files ✔️
(but remember: random writing is also possible)
________________________________________
Final corrected statement (exam-perfect)
Sequential access files allow only sequential reading and writing, whereas random access files allow both sequential and random reading and writing.

A Random Access File (RAF) allows you to:
•	Read and write data in a file
•	Jump to any position in the file (random access)
Unlike FileInputStream or FileReader which read sequentially (start → end), RAF lets you go directly to a specific byte or record.
________________________________________
Key Class
java.io.RandomAccessFile
Constructor syntax:
RandomAccessFile raf = new RandomAccessFile("file.txt", "mode");
•	"r" → read only
•	"rw" → read and write
________________________________________
Important Methods
Method	What it does
read()	Reads next byte
readLine()	Reads next line
write()	Writes bytes
seek(long pos)	Moves file pointer to pos
getFilePointer()	Returns current pointer position
length()	Returns file size in bytes
Tip: seek() is what makes it “random access.”
________________________________________
Concept Example (Pseudo-code)
RandomAccessFile raf = new RandomAccessFile("data.txt", "rw");

// Move to byte 50
raf.seek(50);

// Read a line from there
String s = raf.readLine();

// Move to end of file and write
raf.seek(raf.length());
raf.writeBytes("Hello!");
Key idea: You can jump anywhere, read or write, without touching other data.
Reading and Writing Objects
=======================
1.	Big Idea
Normally, Java files store bytes or text. But sometimes, you want to store entire objects (with their fields and state) in a file and read them back later.
This is called serialization (writing objects) and deserialization (reading objects).
________________________________________
2.	Key Classes
•	ObjectOutputStream → writes objects to a file
•	ObjectInputStream → reads objects from a file
•	FileOutputStream / FileInputStream → used internally for actual file writing
Important: The object class must implement:
java.io.Serializable
________________________________________
3.	How it Works (Conceptually)
1.	Serialization: Java converts an object into bytes → stores in file
2.	Deserialization: Java reads bytes → reconstructs the object
Think of it as saving and loading a game state.
________________________________________ 
4.	Example Concept (Full working example)    

import java.io.*;

class Student implements Serializable {
private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;  	// serialVersionUID is a version number for a 
// Serializable class. UID – Unique Identifier

    int id;
    String name;

    Student(int id, String name) {
        this.id = id;
        this.name = name;
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {

        Student studentObject = new Student(1, "Alice");

        // Writing object
        FileOutputStream fos = new FileOutputStream("student.dat");
        ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(fos);
        oos.writeObject(studentObject);
        oos.close();

        // Reading object
        FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("student.dat");
        ObjectInputStream ois = new ObjectInputStream(fis);
        Student s = (Student) ois.readObject();
        ois.close();

        System.out.println(s.id + " " + s.name);
    }
}

